<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<XMLDocContent PageName="cobalt.logging.Logger" Title="Logger class" xmlns="http://www.cobaltrenderer.com/schema/XMLDocSchema.xsd">
  <Paragraph>
    <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.Welcome">Home</PageRef> ->
    Logger
  </Paragraph>
  <Section Title="Declaration">
    <Code Language="C++"><![CDATA[class Logger : public ILogger;]]></Code>
  </Section>
  <Section Title="Description">
    <Paragraph>
      The <TypeRef>Logger</TypeRef> class is the standard concrete implementation of <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.ILogger">ILogger</PageRef> used by <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.LogManager">LogManager</PageRef>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
      Applications usually do not construct this type directly. The constructor is private to the logging implementation, and logger instances are created through <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.LogManager.GetLogger">LogManager.GetLogger</PageRef>, <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.ILogger.CloneLogger">ILogger.CloneLogger</PageRef>, or <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.ILogger.GetLoggerChildScope">ILogger.GetLoggerChildScope</PageRef>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Note Type="Warning">
      <Paragraph>
        A <TypeRef>Logger</TypeRef> stores a reference to its owning <PageRef PageName="cobalt.logging.LogManager">LogManager</PageRef>. The manager must outlive the logger.
      </Paragraph>
    </Note>
    <Note Type="Important">
      <Paragraph>
        Logger instances are safe to use concurrently from multiple threads.
      </Paragraph>
    </Note>
  </Section>
  <Section Title="Members">
    <SubSection Title="Lifetime methods">
      <FunctionMemberList>
        <FunctionMemberListEntry Visibility="Public" Name="Delete" PageName="cobalt.logging.Logger.Delete">
          Deletes the logger object.
        </FunctionMemberListEntry>
      </FunctionMemberList>
    </SubSection>
  </Section>
